1
00:00:27,527 --> 00:00:29,328
Found a phone!

2
00:00:30,530 --> 00:00:33,532
It looks like it's from 1967,
but I think it'll work.

3
00:00:33,534 --> 00:00:35,367
Just a sec, Jimmy.

4
00:00:35,369 --> 00:00:37,770
Excellent.
Thank you for being so careful.

5
00:00:37,772 --> 00:00:39,304
-Sir.
-Hmm?

6
00:00:39,306 --> 00:00:40,806
-We have to get in your attic.
-For what?

7
00:00:40,808 --> 00:00:42,374
Oh, the hook-up.

8
00:00:42,376 --> 00:00:43,542
Oh, no. That's all right.
Don't bother.

9
00:00:43,544 --> 00:00:45,210
Oh, it won't
take 20 minutes.

10
00:00:45,212 --> 00:00:46,545
Plus, you really can't use it
if I don't do it.

11
00:00:46,547 --> 00:00:48,380
No, it's all right.
We're not gonna.

12
00:00:48,382 --> 00:00:49,715
Uh, when you're
done here,

13
00:00:49,717 --> 00:00:51,483
would you get some more lamps
in the garage?

14
00:00:51,485 --> 00:00:52,684
Thanks.

15
00:00:54,221 --> 00:00:55,587
-So, we got a phone.
-Yeah.

16
00:00:55,589 --> 00:00:57,122
The yard's half-mowed.

17
00:00:57,124 --> 00:00:59,091
Uh, the sockets and stuff
are looking a-ok.

18
00:00:59,093 --> 00:01:01,160
I'm gonna check again
just to make sure.

19
00:01:01,162 --> 00:01:02,394
We're almost there.

20
00:01:02,396 --> 00:01:03,462
Good.
Good.

21
00:01:03,464 --> 00:01:05,831
Um, what do you think?

22
00:01:05,833 --> 00:01:08,333
On? Off?

23
00:01:08,335 --> 00:01:11,370
Ohh.
I think...Off.

24
00:01:11,372 --> 00:01:14,206
Yeah. You're right.
Off it is.

25
00:01:14,208 --> 00:01:15,407
-Chuck.
-Hmm?

26
00:01:15,409 --> 00:01:17,276
You sure this is
the right play?

27
00:01:17,278 --> 00:01:18,744
I mean, in my experience,

28
00:01:18,746 --> 00:01:22,714
the bigger the lie,
the harder it can be to dig out.

29
00:01:22,716 --> 00:01:25,117
I'll cross that bridge
when I come to it.

30
00:01:28,488 --> 00:01:31,156
Hey, guys, think we're set
with the lamps.

31
00:01:31,158 --> 00:01:34,426
Uh, could someone give me a hand
with this phone?<i> Gracias.</i>

32
00:02:29,449 --> 00:02:30,849
Mmm.

33
00:02:49,303 --> 00:02:50,736
It's open!

34
00:02:59,512 --> 00:03:00,812
Rebecca.

35
00:03:00,814 --> 00:03:03,248
-Chuck.
-You look lovely.

36
00:03:03,250 --> 00:03:05,417
- Oh, it's so good to see you.
- And you.

37
00:03:05,419 --> 00:03:06,718
Oh.

38
00:03:06,720 --> 00:03:09,521
Hey,
what's with the candles?

39
00:03:09,523 --> 00:03:10,822
Why you sittin' here
in the dark?

40
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:12,291
Yeah, I was wondering
the same thing.

41
00:03:12,293 --> 00:03:14,927
Oh, my god,
the afternoon I've had.

42
00:03:14,929 --> 00:03:17,462
Two hours ago,
i take the sea bass out.

43
00:03:17,464 --> 00:03:19,631
No sooner is it prepped
and resting

44
00:03:19,633 --> 00:03:22,801
than -- boom! --
Power goes down.

45
00:03:22,803 --> 00:03:24,703
I get on the phone
to the city.

46
00:03:24,705 --> 00:03:26,738
To make a long story short,

47
00:03:26,740 --> 00:03:29,775
those bozos at pnm
mixed up my payment.

48
00:03:29,777 --> 00:03:32,678
The deadbeat
at 512 San Cristobal

49
00:03:32,680 --> 00:03:34,513
hasn't been paying
his bills.

50
00:03:34,515 --> 00:03:35,981
And, of course, I'm...

51
00:03:35,983 --> 00:03:37,449
-215.
-215, exactly.

52
00:03:37,451 --> 00:03:38,884
Mm-hmm. Mm.

53
00:03:38,886 --> 00:03:40,953
They say they'll have it on
again by tomorrow.

54
00:03:40,955 --> 00:03:44,523
In the meantime, I borrowed some
camping gear from my neighbors.

55
00:03:44,525 --> 00:03:45,958
Hence, the rustic flair.

56
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:48,260
-Jeez.
-Oh, yeah.

57
00:03:48,262 --> 00:03:49,595
So, what do we do?

58
00:03:49,597 --> 00:03:51,330
Uh, get out of here
and go to a restaurant?

59
00:03:51,332 --> 00:03:54,266
We could hit seasons.
Your treat.

60
00:03:54,268 --> 00:03:55,867
We could, yeah.

61
00:03:55,869 --> 00:03:59,238
But, um, you know,
dinner's almost ready.

62
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:01,440
And the fish -- I would have
just had to throw it out.

63
00:04:01,442 --> 00:04:02,975
All I have to do is toss it
in a pan.

64
00:04:02,977 --> 00:04:04,776
How about
we just rough it?

65
00:04:04,778 --> 00:04:06,245
Huh?
You okay with that?

66
00:04:06,247 --> 00:04:07,879
Uh, um...

67
00:04:07,881 --> 00:04:10,949
Well...Why not?
It'll be fun.

68
00:04:10,951 --> 00:04:13,785
We'll do
an haute-cuisine camp-out.

69
00:04:13,787 --> 00:04:16,021
Great! Then it's settled.
Let me take that.

70
00:04:16,023 --> 00:04:17,656
-Take your...
-Oh, yeah, here.

71
00:04:17,658 --> 00:04:19,424
-Here, I'll take that.
-Oh, thank you. Mm-hmm.

72
00:04:21,728 --> 00:04:22,928
-Mmm.
-Mmm.

73
00:04:22,930 --> 00:04:24,930
Oh, my god.

74
00:04:24,932 --> 00:04:26,698
I can't eat
another bite.

75
00:04:29,736 --> 00:04:32,471
Cheers to
the galloping gourmet.

76
00:04:32,473 --> 00:04:33,572
-Mm!
-Ah.

77
00:04:33,574 --> 00:04:34,673
Yeah.

78
00:04:34,675 --> 00:04:36,341
Mm.

79
00:04:37,477 --> 00:04:38,944
The calvados
is perfect.

80
00:04:38,946 --> 00:04:40,846
Mm.
You always liked it.

81
00:04:40,848 --> 00:04:42,781
Here.

82
00:04:42,783 --> 00:04:44,583
Uh, um.
Let me get this.

83
00:04:44,585 --> 00:04:45,984
No, no, Jimmy.
You don't have to.

84
00:04:45,986 --> 00:04:47,886
No, least I can do
is the dishes.
Oh.

85
00:04:47,888 --> 00:04:50,489
Thank you.

86
00:04:50,491 --> 00:04:51,790
Thanks, Jimmy.

87
00:04:55,061 --> 00:04:57,462
This turned out better
than I thought.

88
00:04:57,464 --> 00:05:00,632
Uh, I'm so...Sorry
about the lights.

89
00:05:00,634 --> 00:05:03,935
Oh, it's nice.
Atmospheric.

90
00:05:03,937 --> 00:05:07,906
I mean, I still can't get over
Jimmy being a lawyer.

91
00:05:07,908 --> 00:05:09,441
Neither can I.

92
00:05:09,443 --> 00:05:11,910
He's got his own shingle out
and everything.

93
00:05:11,912 --> 00:05:13,812
I mean, a real,
responsible citizen.

94
00:05:13,814 --> 00:05:15,414
I mean,
who woulda thought?

95
00:05:15,416 --> 00:05:18,583
Yeah.

96
00:05:18,585 --> 00:05:21,320
Mm.

97
00:05:21,322 --> 00:05:22,988
This place
is the same.

98
00:05:22,990 --> 00:05:25,057
I mean,
i-i would've thought you'd

99
00:05:25,059 --> 00:05:28,860
Change things up.

100
00:05:28,862 --> 00:05:30,462
Move things around.

101
00:05:30,464 --> 00:05:33,098
You've got great taste.
And if it ain't broke...

102
00:05:34,067 --> 00:05:35,567
How's the tour going?

103
00:05:35,569 --> 00:05:36,802
It's good.
Good.

104
00:05:36,804 --> 00:05:38,670
Um, the far east this fall.

105
00:05:38,672 --> 00:05:40,806
Uh, China, south Korea,
and Vietnam.

106
00:05:40,808 --> 00:05:42,908
That's gonna be exciting.
Yeah.

107
00:05:42,910 --> 00:05:45,477
And then, um,
after Santa fe this week,

108
00:05:45,479 --> 00:05:47,045
uh, we're back
to central Europe.

109
00:05:47,047 --> 00:05:48,480
And it's good?

110
00:05:48,482 --> 00:05:50,082
Well, it's a lot of hotels.
Yeah.

111
00:05:50,084 --> 00:05:52,484
I mean, in Budapest,
i think I saw mostly

112
00:05:52,486 --> 00:05:54,920
the inside of the concert hall
and the marriott.

113
00:05:54,922 --> 00:05:58,090
But, you know,
i shouldn't complain.

114
00:05:58,092 --> 00:06:00,826
You're not complaining.
You're<i> observing.</i>

115
00:06:04,564 --> 00:06:06,531
Did you finally
get to see salzburg?

116
00:06:06,533 --> 00:06:08,967
Not yet,
but next month, after Vienna.

117
00:06:08,969 --> 00:06:11,770
Do you remember when we tried
to go to salzburg?

118
00:06:11,772 --> 00:06:14,106
And that crazy old lady
on the scooter...

119
00:06:14,108 --> 00:06:15,941
Oh, yes! Yes!
...Chased us out
of the train station.

120
00:06:15,943 --> 00:06:17,509
Yeah!

121
00:06:17,511 --> 00:06:19,878
And then, um --
and then we went and got, uh,

122
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:23,515
it was a-a-a raspberry
linzer torte in innsbruck?

123
00:06:23,517 --> 00:06:25,484
Mm.
To make ourselves
feel better?

124
00:06:25,486 --> 00:06:27,786
Mm. You said,
"we'll never finish this!"

125
00:06:27,788 --> 00:06:30,655
And then we did.

126
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:34,826
So, what's after Asia?
Any plans for a stateside tour?

127
00:06:34,828 --> 00:06:36,962
Oh, you know,
hopefully next year.

128
00:06:36,964 --> 00:06:40,065
You know, maybe a residency.
Oh, that would be sweet.

129
00:06:40,067 --> 00:06:41,600
I mean, you know,
i like the buses

130
00:06:41,602 --> 00:06:45,537
and trains and planes fine,
but I, um...

131
00:06:45,539 --> 00:06:49,141
I miss having one --
one place to hang my hat.

132
00:06:54,948 --> 00:06:57,115
Oh, god!

133
00:06:57,117 --> 00:06:59,818
I'm sorry.
I-i-i hate that thing.

134
00:06:59,820 --> 00:07:02,954
I feel like I'm on a leash.
Ugh!

135
00:07:02,956 --> 00:07:04,856
I'm sorry.

136
00:07:08,561 --> 00:07:10,662
Oh.
Oh, it's my conductor.

137
00:07:10,664 --> 00:07:13,198
Um, I have to take this.
I'm sorry.

138
00:07:13,200 --> 00:07:15,100
H-hi, Andre.

139
00:07:15,102 --> 00:07:17,536
No, I'm just at dinner.
What's up?

140
00:07:18,571 --> 00:07:19,805
Well, I can do that
at rehearsal.

141
00:07:19,807 --> 00:07:21,740
Yeah, no problem.
Yeah.

142
00:07:21,742 --> 00:07:25,210
No, i-i know that they're
coming in late on bar 16.

143
00:07:25,212 --> 00:07:27,846
Y-yeah.
Got it. Got it.

144
00:07:27,848 --> 00:07:29,714
I will make sure that --

145
00:07:29,716 --> 00:07:31,583
uh, c-c-can you hold on
a second?

146
00:07:31,585 --> 00:07:32,884
Let me just get a pen.

147
00:07:32,886 --> 00:07:34,920
Mm-hmm.

148
00:07:34,922 --> 00:07:38,490
Yeah.
No, i-i...

149
00:07:38,492 --> 00:07:40,525
Yeah,
hold on one second.

150
00:07:40,527 --> 00:07:42,627
Yeah, I can do it --
i mean, whatever you need.

151
00:07:42,629 --> 00:07:44,095
Mm-hmm.
Okay.

152
00:07:44,097 --> 00:07:45,497
All right, shoot.

153
00:07:46,700 --> 00:07:48,667
Okay...

154
00:07:50,637 --> 00:07:51,703
Chuck?

155
00:07:51,705 --> 00:07:53,505
I'm all right.

156
00:07:53,507 --> 00:07:56,541
Well, do you want me to rehearse
the cellists separately?

157
00:07:56,543 --> 00:07:57,943
- Jimmy: Rebecca.
- Rebecca.

158
00:08:00,947 --> 00:08:03,915
Well, no, it's not just him.
It's the whole section.

159
00:08:03,917 --> 00:08:04,983
Rebecca!

160
00:08:04,985 --> 00:08:06,852
Uh, no.

161
00:08:06,854 --> 00:08:09,020
T-that's fine.

162
00:08:09,022 --> 00:08:10,589
Yeah.

163
00:08:10,591 --> 00:08:12,591
Chuck, what the hell?!

164
00:08:15,261 --> 00:08:17,162
Andre?

165
00:08:17,164 --> 00:08:19,631
I-i-i have to --
I'll have to call you back.

166
00:08:19,633 --> 00:08:20,932
I'm sorry.

167
00:08:22,768 --> 00:08:24,569
What is your problem?

168
00:08:26,940 --> 00:08:28,874
Say something.

169
00:08:33,145 --> 00:08:35,814
It is
incredibly bad manners

170
00:08:35,816 --> 00:08:38,750
to answer a cellphone
in company.

171
00:08:38,752 --> 00:08:40,519
It's very rude.

172
00:08:40,521 --> 00:08:43,722
Uh, i-I'm sorry.

173
00:08:43,724 --> 00:08:46,825
I-i didn't know
that you felt that way.

174
00:08:46,827 --> 00:08:49,995
I...Didn't mean to offend you,
Chuck.

175
00:08:49,997 --> 00:08:52,130
I-i may have overreacted.

176
00:08:52,132 --> 00:08:53,532
That was very abrupt.

177
00:08:53,534 --> 00:08:54,533
-No.
-Uh.

178
00:08:54,535 --> 00:08:56,801
I understand.

179
00:08:58,171 --> 00:09:00,639
Uh...

180
00:09:00,641 --> 00:09:02,173
It's getting late.

181
00:09:02,175 --> 00:09:03,808
Thank you
for a lovely dinner,

182
00:09:03,810 --> 00:09:06,278
but I should be getting back
to the hotel.

183
00:09:06,280 --> 00:09:08,079
Just gimme a minute,
and we can --

184
00:09:08,081 --> 00:09:10,215
no. Uh, um,
I'll just get a cab.

185
00:09:10,217 --> 00:09:12,083
I don't want to put you out
any more than I already --
please, let me.

186
00:09:12,085 --> 00:09:13,585
No, really.

187
00:09:13,587 --> 00:09:15,654
A cab is the easiest.

188
00:09:17,590 --> 00:09:18,890
You gotta do somethin'.

189
00:09:18,892 --> 00:09:20,692
Y-you can't let her leave
like this.

190
00:09:20,694 --> 00:09:22,027
Just tell her
what's going on.

191
00:09:22,029 --> 00:09:23,295
No. No.

192
00:09:23,297 --> 00:09:24,996
She'll understand.

193
00:09:24,998 --> 00:09:27,699
She'll -- would you rather
she think you're a raging prick

194
00:09:27,701 --> 00:09:28,833
than know the truth?

195
00:09:28,835 --> 00:09:30,869
No.

196
00:09:30,871 --> 00:09:32,737
Look, if you won't tell her,
then I will.

197
00:09:32,739 --> 00:09:34,639
No, no. No!

198
00:09:34,641 --> 00:09:36,841
You will not tell her.

199
00:09:36,843 --> 00:09:40,178
You...Will not tell her.

200
00:09:40,180 --> 00:09:42,280
All right.

201
00:09:42,282 --> 00:09:45,183
Hi, Andre.
Yes, I'm sorry about that.

202
00:09:45,185 --> 00:09:47,118
I dropped the phone.

203
00:10:20,987 --> 00:10:22,954
Caldera: Jesus.
What're you doing, man?

204
00:10:22,956 --> 00:10:24,923
There's barely any oxygen
in that bag.

205
00:10:24,925 --> 00:10:26,958
-You're suffocating her!
-"Her"?

206
00:10:26,960 --> 00:10:29,394
Yeah, just because
you don't see swingin' dicks

207
00:10:29,396 --> 00:10:32,364
doesn't mean you can't tell
a boy fish from a girl fish.

208
00:10:32,366 --> 00:10:34,165
Oh, yeah, see.

209
00:10:34,167 --> 00:10:36,034
Now I can see
the lipstick.

210
00:10:36,036 --> 00:10:39,237
This is a living creature.
It's not a piece of furniture.

211
00:10:39,239 --> 00:10:41,239
So, after this,
you take her home.

212
00:10:41,241 --> 00:10:43,875
You put her in a big bowl,
at least a gallon.

213
00:10:43,877 --> 00:10:47,345
Get a good bubbler,
maybe a plecostomus.

214
00:10:47,347 --> 00:10:49,247
And don't feed her
too much.

215
00:10:49,249 --> 00:10:50,682
People get fat.

216
00:10:50,684 --> 00:10:52,384
Fish, they drown
in leftover food.

217
00:10:52,386 --> 00:10:54,386
All right already,
Jacques cousteau.

218
00:10:54,388 --> 00:10:55,887
Point made.

219
00:10:55,889 --> 00:10:57,288
Good.

220
00:10:59,892 --> 00:11:02,861
I'm guessing our friend
didn't refer you to me

221
00:11:02,863 --> 00:11:05,797
to get
ichthyological advice.

222
00:11:05,799 --> 00:11:08,867
I'm looking for someone
with a light touch.

223
00:11:08,869 --> 00:11:11,703
I'm not talking some teenager
taking a five-finger discount

224
00:11:11,705 --> 00:11:13,438
on string cheese
at the stop 'n' shop.

225
00:11:13,440 --> 00:11:18,410
I need highly skilled,
high-end, discreet.

226
00:11:18,412 --> 00:11:20,445
A real pro.

227
00:11:20,447 --> 00:11:23,415
You gotta fit him
in a tight space?

228
00:11:23,417 --> 00:11:25,316
I don't think so.

229
00:11:27,420 --> 00:11:30,055
I got just the guy,
then.

230
00:11:47,273 --> 00:11:49,808
That's why I say golfing
is a contact sport.

231
00:11:52,045 --> 00:11:55,080
Great job, Ms. wexler.
Very refreshing.

232
00:11:55,082 --> 00:11:58,249
Believe me, uh, we're happy
to get this one off the docket.

233
00:11:58,251 --> 00:11:59,851
Not as happy
as we are.

234
00:11:59,853 --> 00:12:01,252
Again, great job.

235
00:12:01,254 --> 00:12:02,821
Thank you.
Thank you, sir.

236
00:12:07,226 --> 00:12:09,928
Ladies,
dinner's on me.

237
00:12:11,732 --> 00:12:13,431
Kim, I knew you were good, but i
didn't know you were this good.

238
00:12:13,433 --> 00:12:15,900
Oh, I'm glad
you're happy.

239
00:12:15,902 --> 00:12:18,036
We couldn't have done it
without you.

240
00:12:18,038 --> 00:12:20,805
And I hope you realize
this means a whole lot
a work comin' your way.

241
00:12:20,807 --> 00:12:23,341
Oh, that's --
that's great.

242
00:12:24,276 --> 00:12:26,144
Well, you don't sound
like it's great.

243
00:12:27,847 --> 00:12:29,080
I hate to be a buzzkill,

244
00:12:29,082 --> 00:12:31,049
but there is something
you need to hear

245
00:12:31,051 --> 00:12:32,484
before we get
any deeper in.

246
00:12:32,486 --> 00:12:35,987
It's about your former attorney,
Charles mcgill.

247
00:12:35,989 --> 00:12:37,122
What about him?

248
00:12:37,124 --> 00:12:38,790
Charles has been making

249
00:12:38,792 --> 00:12:41,960
some very ugly allegations
about his brother, Jimmy,

250
00:12:41,962 --> 00:12:44,763
with whom I happen to share
an office space.

251
00:12:44,765 --> 00:12:48,500
Allegations?
Of what?

252
00:12:48,502 --> 00:12:50,068
Charles thinks that Jimmy

253
00:12:50,070 --> 00:12:52,337
somehow took control
of your documents

254
00:12:52,339 --> 00:12:54,906
while he was working on them
at his home.

255
00:12:54,908 --> 00:12:56,941
He believes Jimmy transposed
the address numbers.

256
00:12:56,943 --> 00:12:59,077
Transposed the numbers?

257
00:12:59,079 --> 00:13:01,846
How would he
even do that?

258
00:13:01,848 --> 00:13:04,516
Charles contends that Jimmy
took the documents

259
00:13:04,518 --> 00:13:06,785
pertaining
to the rosella branch

260
00:13:06,787 --> 00:13:08,953
and, while Charles
was indisposed,

261
00:13:08,955 --> 00:13:11,489
photocopied
and doctored them.

262
00:13:11,491 --> 00:13:14,492
That's pretty baroque.

263
00:13:14,494 --> 00:13:16,060
The important thing here

264
00:13:16,062 --> 00:13:18,129
is I think it could make
some noise in public.

265
00:13:18,131 --> 00:13:19,898
Soon.

266
00:13:19,900 --> 00:13:22,066
I wanted to tell you this in
the spirit of full disclosure.

267
00:13:22,068 --> 00:13:24,002
I thought it was better
if you heard it from me.

268
00:13:26,305 --> 00:13:29,274
If you have any reservations
at this point

269
00:13:29,276 --> 00:13:32,443
or if you are not comfortable
staying with me,

270
00:13:32,445 --> 00:13:34,212
we can discuss options.

271
00:13:39,285 --> 00:13:41,419
If there's one thing
i cannot abide,

272
00:13:41,421 --> 00:13:43,555
it's a man who won't
own up to his mistakes.

273
00:13:43,557 --> 00:13:48,159
Now, whatever mud mcgill
is slinging he's not gonna

274
00:13:48,161 --> 00:13:53,164
screw me out of the best
outside counsel I've ever had.

275
00:13:53,166 --> 00:13:56,167
That's...

276
00:13:56,169 --> 00:13:58,036
I'm so glad
to hear that.

277
00:13:58,038 --> 00:13:59,337
We appreciate
the heads-up,

278
00:13:59,339 --> 00:14:00,872
but you can call this baby
put to bed.

279
00:14:00,874 --> 00:14:02,173
Now the most important thing --
dinner.

280
00:14:02,175 --> 00:14:04,309
7:00 good for you?

281
00:14:04,311 --> 00:14:06,211
-Uh, works for me.
-Great.

282
00:14:06,213 --> 00:14:07,879
We'll talk strategy --

283
00:14:07,881 --> 00:14:10,048
we move on Colorado
or Utah first?

284
00:14:10,050 --> 00:14:13,051
See ya at 7:00.

285
00:14:13,053 --> 00:14:14,586
This mcgill thing.

286
00:14:14,588 --> 00:14:18,189
You're sure it's not
gonna be a problem?

287
00:14:18,191 --> 00:14:20,058
I am.

288
00:14:20,060 --> 00:14:23,895
Mesa verde isn't involved
in any way, shape, or form.

289
00:14:23,897 --> 00:14:27,232
Okay. Good.

290
00:14:27,234 --> 00:14:29,067
Then,
I'll see you tonight.

291
00:14:29,069 --> 00:14:30,635
Okay, great.
See you then.

292
00:14:47,520 --> 00:14:49,454
Alley:
Okay, this is it.

293
00:14:49,456 --> 00:14:51,356
We can run without lights
and mics.

294
00:14:51,358 --> 00:14:53,024
We'll collect all cellphones

295
00:14:53,026 --> 00:14:55,226
and hold them for the duration
of your testimony.

296
00:14:55,228 --> 00:14:57,395
The, uh, court reporter,
would it be possible

297
00:14:57,397 --> 00:14:59,931
to move him or her farther
from the witness stand?

298
00:14:59,933 --> 00:15:01,232
Um, yeah,
i think we can arrange

299
00:15:01,234 --> 00:15:02,667
having them
in the back of the court.

300
00:15:04,504 --> 00:15:07,038
I'm sorry. There's nothing
i can do about the exit signs.

301
00:15:07,040 --> 00:15:08,206
It's code.

302
00:15:08,208 --> 00:15:09,574
I appreciate
all you're doing.

303
00:15:09,576 --> 00:15:11,009
Thank you.

304
00:15:13,046 --> 00:15:15,013
Mr. alley, I wonder
if you'd give us a moment.

305
00:15:15,015 --> 00:15:17,015
I'd like to go over something
with my colleague.

306
00:15:17,017 --> 00:15:18,950
No problem. I'll be outside
when you're ready.

307
00:15:20,686 --> 00:15:23,087
Howard?

308
00:15:23,089 --> 00:15:25,423
How you feeling, Chuck?

309
00:15:25,425 --> 00:15:27,425
I'll muddle through.

310
00:15:27,427 --> 00:15:29,460
Because this is
a lot to ask.

311
00:15:29,462 --> 00:15:32,463
And if you're not up to it --
just throwing this out there --

312
00:15:32,465 --> 00:15:34,198
maybe you don't need
to testify at all.

313
00:15:34,200 --> 00:15:35,633
No,<i> I</i> do.

314
00:15:35,635 --> 00:15:37,602
I'm the only person
who can adequately explain

315
00:15:37,604 --> 00:15:39,237
the context of that tape.

316
00:15:39,239 --> 00:15:41,539
Otherwise, the defense'll
tear it to shreds.

317
00:15:41,541 --> 00:15:43,274
It's already
a solid case.

318
00:15:43,276 --> 00:15:46,444
We have Jimmy's statement from
the pre-prosecution diversion.

319
00:15:46,446 --> 00:15:48,980
There's my testimony
and the private eye's.

320
00:15:48,982 --> 00:15:52,684
Maybe there's no need to put you
through the wringer like this.

321
00:15:52,686 --> 00:15:55,954
This isn't about me
or my health.

322
00:15:55,956 --> 00:15:58,323
This is about PR.

323
00:15:58,325 --> 00:16:00,358
We lost a client.

324
00:16:00,360 --> 00:16:04,595
That happened because,
while you were...Incapacitated,

325
00:16:04,597 --> 00:16:06,698
your brother
accessed documents

326
00:16:06,700 --> 00:16:09,233
that should have been secured
at hhm.

327
00:16:09,235 --> 00:16:13,204
What Jimmy did
is unconscionable, yes...

328
00:16:13,206 --> 00:16:16,574
But one of my jobs is to
safeguard the firm's reputation.

329
00:16:16,576 --> 00:16:19,477
This is not the time
to worry about how we look.

330
00:16:19,479 --> 00:16:22,213
This is about what's right
and what's wrong.

331
00:16:22,215 --> 00:16:24,382
I'm not gonna risk
Jimmy getting, what?

332
00:16:24,384 --> 00:16:27,552
A year's suspension?
Maybe two?

333
00:16:27,554 --> 00:16:31,222
He deserves<i> disbarment,</i>
not some slap on the wrist.

334
00:16:31,224 --> 00:16:34,659
No, Howard.
There's only one way forward.

335
00:16:35,761 --> 00:16:39,063
Let justice be done,
though the heavens fall.

336
00:16:41,034 --> 00:16:44,002
Sorry to keep you waiting.
This'll do nicely.

337
00:16:44,004 --> 00:16:47,672
Please extend my thanks to the
committee for their flexibility.

338
00:16:49,608 --> 00:16:53,177
Alley: Good morning. I'm
Robert alley for the state bar.

339
00:16:53,179 --> 00:16:55,213
In the matter
of James m. Mcgill,

340
00:16:55,215 --> 00:16:57,615
the state bar intends to prove
the following violations

341
00:16:57,617 --> 00:16:59,450
of the ethical code.

342
00:16:59,452 --> 00:17:05,289
16-102 -- engaging in conduct
a lawyer knows is criminal.

343
00:17:05,291 --> 00:17:08,359
Mr. mcgill certainly knew that
breaking down his brother's door

344
00:17:08,361 --> 00:17:10,528
was criminal behavior.

345
00:17:10,530 --> 00:17:15,733
16-804 -- committing a criminal
act that reflects adversely

346
00:17:15,735 --> 00:17:20,171
on the lawyer's honesty
or trustworthiness as a lawyer.

347
00:17:20,173 --> 00:17:22,106
Any reasonable person
would agree

348
00:17:22,108 --> 00:17:24,542
that assaulting another lawyer
in his own home

349
00:17:24,544 --> 00:17:29,547
reflects badly on Mr. mcgill's
fitness as an attorney.

350
00:17:29,549 --> 00:17:34,452
16-304 -- unlawfully altering,
destroying,

351
00:17:34,454 --> 00:17:38,556
or concealing material having
potential evidentiary value.

352
00:17:38,558 --> 00:17:40,825
Mr. mcgill broke into
his brother's home

353
00:17:40,827 --> 00:17:42,627
and destroyed an audiocassette

354
00:17:42,629 --> 00:17:45,363
which contained a recording
of a conversation

355
00:17:45,365 --> 00:17:48,232
between himself and his brother,
Charles mcgill.

356
00:17:48,234 --> 00:17:50,368
We will show that this recording
was evidence

357
00:17:50,370 --> 00:17:52,403
in an ongoing legal case.

358
00:17:53,405 --> 00:17:54,772
The state bar believes that,

359
00:17:54,774 --> 00:17:56,674
once we have presented
the facts,

360
00:17:56,676 --> 00:17:59,477
the committee will agree
that disbarment is warranted

361
00:17:59,479 --> 00:18:01,813
for James mcgill.

362
00:18:01,815 --> 00:18:04,816
Thank you very much.

363
00:18:04,818 --> 00:18:06,684
Thank you,
Mr. alley.

364
00:18:06,686 --> 00:18:08,152
Ms. wexler?

365
00:18:13,525 --> 00:18:16,494
Thank you, Mr. chairman.

366
00:18:16,496 --> 00:18:20,865
I'm Kim wexler, co-counsel with
James mcgill, for the defense.

367
00:18:20,867 --> 00:18:24,469
You've already read Mr. mcgill's
pre-prosecution statement.

368
00:18:24,471 --> 00:18:27,572
We don't dispute he broke into
his brother's house,

369
00:18:27,574 --> 00:18:31,676
an act he regrets...Deeply.

370
00:18:31,678 --> 00:18:34,345
But there is another side
to this story.

371
00:18:34,347 --> 00:18:40,284
One not about calculation
or ill intent,

372
00:18:40,286 --> 00:18:42,587
but about about two brothers,

373
00:18:42,589 --> 00:18:47,158
whose relationship,
after years of strain,

374
00:18:47,160 --> 00:18:48,593
finally broke.

375
00:18:50,496 --> 00:18:53,664
We believe that, after you
have the complete picture,

376
00:18:53,666 --> 00:18:56,267
you'll understand
James mcgill is an asset

377
00:18:56,269 --> 00:18:58,136
to our legal community.

378
00:18:58,138 --> 00:19:01,472
And he should remain a full
member of it in good standing.

379
00:19:02,908 --> 00:19:04,542
Thank you.

380
00:19:06,245 --> 00:19:08,346
Thank you,
Ms. wexler.

381
00:19:11,450 --> 00:19:16,888
Okay, if, uh, everyone's ready
to begin testimony...

382
00:19:16,890 --> 00:19:19,223
Mr. alley,
call your witness.

383
00:19:19,225 --> 00:19:20,825
Hamlin:
Bang! Bang! Bang!

384
00:19:20,827 --> 00:19:22,627
Then he kicked down the door.

385
00:19:22,629 --> 00:19:24,695
Jimmy was very agitated.
He was shouting.

386
00:19:24,697 --> 00:19:26,564
He demanded Charles turn over

387
00:19:26,566 --> 00:19:28,766
the evidence
he'd been collecting --
Kim: Objection.

388
00:19:28,768 --> 00:19:31,602
We haven't established the tape
is "evidence" of anything.

389
00:19:31,604 --> 00:19:34,605
The defense has only
acknowledged it as
a piece of property.

390
00:19:34,607 --> 00:19:37,575
Uh, allow me
to rephrase.

391
00:19:37,577 --> 00:19:40,878
Jimmy demanded an audiocassette
in Charles' possession,

392
00:19:40,880 --> 00:19:42,413
which Jimmy proceeded,

393
00:19:42,415 --> 00:19:45,283
with the help of
an iron fireplace implement,

394
00:19:45,285 --> 00:19:46,784
to pry from Charles' desk.

395
00:19:46,786 --> 00:19:49,353
He then broke the cassette
into pieces

396
00:19:49,355 --> 00:19:51,656
and went on
to confront his brother.

397
00:19:51,658 --> 00:19:54,659
What happened after the
defendant smashed this tape?

398
00:19:54,661 --> 00:19:56,227
Mr. brightbill
and I --

399
00:19:56,229 --> 00:19:57,395
that's the
private investigator

400
00:19:57,397 --> 00:19:58,462
that Charles hired?

401
00:19:58,464 --> 00:20:00,264
That's correct.

402
00:20:00,266 --> 00:20:03,801
He and I were concerned that
Jimmy might strike his brother.

403
00:20:03,803 --> 00:20:05,703
So that's when
we stepped in.

404
00:20:05,705 --> 00:20:07,872
Thank you, Mr. Hamlin.
Certainly.

405
00:20:07,874 --> 00:20:09,373
Nothing further
at this time.

406
00:20:09,375 --> 00:20:11,442
Man: Ms. wexler?

407
00:20:12,679 --> 00:20:14,512
Kim:
Thank you, Mr. chairman.

408
00:20:17,750 --> 00:20:18,916
Torrent downloaded from RARBG

409
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:25,890
You testified you've known
my client for some time.

410
00:20:25,892 --> 00:20:27,992
How long exactly?

411
00:20:27,994 --> 00:20:29,727
Nearly 10 years.

412
00:20:29,729 --> 00:20:31,629
How did you come
to know him?

413
00:20:31,631 --> 00:20:34,832
His brother asked to hire him
in the mailroom at our firm.

414
00:20:34,834 --> 00:20:37,568
And you did.
Yes.

415
00:20:37,570 --> 00:20:39,437
What was your opinion
of him then?

416
00:20:40,907 --> 00:20:43,674
I thought

417
00:20:43,676 --> 00:20:46,377
He had a lot
of get-up-and-go.

418
00:20:46,379 --> 00:20:47,745
He was a hard worker.

419
00:20:47,747 --> 00:20:50,881
You had a nickname for him,
didn't you?

420
00:20:50,883 --> 00:20:52,316
"Charlie hustle."

421
00:20:52,318 --> 00:20:54,485
"Charlie hustle."

422
00:20:54,487 --> 00:20:56,821
How'd you feel when you
found out he'd become a lawyer?

423
00:20:56,823 --> 00:20:58,022
Surprised.

424
00:20:58,024 --> 00:20:59,857
He'd put himself
through law school

425
00:20:59,859 --> 00:21:02,426
and taken the bar exam without
telling any of the partners.

426
00:21:02,428 --> 00:21:03,728
Even Charles.

427
00:21:03,730 --> 00:21:05,930
He bootstrapped his way
into a law degree

428
00:21:05,932 --> 00:21:07,765
while working
in your mailroom.

429
00:21:07,767 --> 00:21:10,434
Did you consider taking him on
as an associate?

430
00:21:10,436 --> 00:21:12,303
We did.

431
00:21:12,305 --> 00:21:13,571
Briefly.

432
00:21:13,573 --> 00:21:15,039
Sounds like
you<i> didn't</i> hire him.

433
00:21:15,041 --> 00:21:17,475
Why not?
With that kind of grit.

434
00:21:17,477 --> 00:21:19,677
The partners decided
it would be best

435
00:21:19,679 --> 00:21:21,812
to avoid the appearance
of nepotism.

436
00:21:21,814 --> 00:21:25,016
We felt hiring Jimmy
might damage morale.

437
00:21:26,018 --> 00:21:27,985
Nepotism.

438
00:21:27,987 --> 00:21:31,022
Your firm is "Hamlin, Hamlin,
and mcgill," right?

439
00:21:31,024 --> 00:21:32,690
Who's the other Hamlin?

440
00:21:35,527 --> 00:21:36,761
My father.

441
00:21:40,932 --> 00:21:45,303
Which partner was the most
concerned with nepotism?

442
00:21:45,305 --> 00:21:47,471
Charles mcgill.

443
00:21:47,473 --> 00:21:49,373
So Jimmy's own brother
blocked him.

444
00:21:49,375 --> 00:21:50,875
Alley: Objection.

445
00:21:50,877 --> 00:21:52,643
How are the hiring practices
of Hamlin, Hamlin, mcgill

446
00:21:52,645 --> 00:21:53,678
relevant here?

447
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:55,379
It's relevant
to understand

448
00:21:55,381 --> 00:21:57,581
the relationship
between these brothers.

449
00:21:57,583 --> 00:22:01,619
We'll, uh, give you some leeway,
Ms. wexler,

450
00:22:01,621 --> 00:22:03,421
but don't stray
too far.

451
00:22:03,423 --> 00:22:05,723
Charles mcgill is not
the subject of this hearing.

452
00:22:05,725 --> 00:22:07,591
Thank you.

453
00:22:07,593 --> 00:22:09,694
Did Jimmy know
his brother was the one

454
00:22:09,696 --> 00:22:11,662
that prevented you
from hiring him?

455
00:22:11,664 --> 00:22:14,098
Hamlin:
No. He did not.

456
00:22:14,100 --> 00:22:17,535
Eventually, he was hired
by the firm of Davis & main.

457
00:22:17,537 --> 00:22:20,938
I'd be happy to say more
about<i> that,</i> if you'd like.

458
00:22:20,940 --> 00:22:23,674
No. Thank you.

459
00:22:23,676 --> 00:22:25,743
When Charles' condition
appeared,

460
00:22:25,745 --> 00:22:27,878
Jimmy took care of him,
didn't he?

461
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:29,513
I believe so.

462
00:22:29,515 --> 00:22:32,350
Jimmy was struggling
to build his solo law practice,

463
00:22:32,352 --> 00:22:34,518
and yet, every single day,
without fail,

464
00:22:34,520 --> 00:22:36,987
he brought his brother food,
supplies --

465
00:22:36,989 --> 00:22:38,989
even his favorite
newspapers.

466
00:22:38,991 --> 00:22:42,426
-Isn't that right?
-He did.

467
00:22:42,428 --> 00:22:46,597
Could you speak to the terms
of Charles' leave of absence?

468
00:22:46,599 --> 00:22:48,366
You know I can't.

469
00:22:48,368 --> 00:22:51,635
It was an fmla leave.
Anything more is confidential.

470
00:22:51,637 --> 00:22:53,771
But you can confirm it was due
to mental illness, correct?

471
00:22:53,773 --> 00:22:56,974
Objection! Charles mcgill's
mental health isn't at issue.

472
00:22:56,976 --> 00:22:59,877
This is a smear job on the
state bar's upcoming witness --

473
00:22:59,879 --> 00:23:01,145
nothing more.

474
00:23:01,147 --> 00:23:03,481
This is not a competency
hearing, Ms. wexler.

475
00:23:03,483 --> 00:23:05,549
Mr. Hamlin is not a
psychiatric professional.

476
00:23:05,551 --> 00:23:07,585
Do you have any questions
that would be more germane

477
00:23:07,587 --> 00:23:09,954
to his experience?

478
00:23:09,956 --> 00:23:11,622
No.

479
00:23:11,624 --> 00:23:13,524
I have nothing further.

480
00:23:14,092 --> 00:23:16,427
The witness is excused.

481
00:23:27,973 --> 00:23:29,740
Alley: At this time,
the state bar would like

482
00:23:29,742 --> 00:23:31,642
to enter exhibit five
into evidence.

483
00:23:31,644 --> 00:23:33,944
We ask that Charles mcgill's
recording be played.

484
00:23:33,946 --> 00:23:35,679
I'm respectfully renewing
my objection.

485
00:23:35,681 --> 00:23:37,481
The probative value
of playing this exhibit

486
00:23:37,483 --> 00:23:39,016
is outweighed
by how prejudicial it is.

487
00:23:39,018 --> 00:23:40,751
All due respect
to Ms. wexler,

488
00:23:40,753 --> 00:23:42,853
but the state bar feels
this is fundamental to hear.

489
00:23:42,855 --> 00:23:44,488
We don't want to leave
any question

490
00:23:44,490 --> 00:23:45,990
as to the intentions
of both parties.

491
00:23:45,992 --> 00:23:48,092
Ms. wexler, we already ruled
this was fair game

492
00:23:48,094 --> 00:23:50,594
when we denied your motion
to suppress.

493
00:23:50,596 --> 00:23:54,064
I'll add, the rough-and-tumble
of your client's conduct aside,

494
00:23:54,066 --> 00:23:55,900
we need to know
whether one lawyer

495
00:23:55,902 --> 00:23:58,102
attempted to tamper
with another's evidence.

496
00:24:10,649 --> 00:24:12,216
Come here.

497
00:24:12,218 --> 00:24:14,485
What are you still doing here?

498
00:24:14,487 --> 00:24:15,519
Flight's delayed.

499
00:24:15,521 --> 00:24:16,887
How delayed?

500
00:24:16,889 --> 00:24:18,756
40 minutes,
last I checked.

501
00:24:18,758 --> 00:24:21,992
Shit.
Okay. Keep me posted.

502
00:24:23,996 --> 00:24:25,563
Alley: Um, yes.

503
00:24:25,565 --> 00:24:28,132
Here we go.

504
00:24:29,935 --> 00:24:31,469
Thank you
for your Patience.

505
00:24:31,471 --> 00:24:33,003
The state bar
is ready to proceed.

506
00:24:33,005 --> 00:24:35,139
Um, begging your pardon.

507
00:24:35,141 --> 00:24:38,175
Um, the defense requests
a moment to review, if we could?

508
00:24:40,245 --> 00:24:41,812
All right.

509
00:24:41,814 --> 00:24:43,581
When you're ready.

510
00:24:43,583 --> 00:24:45,115
Thank you,
Mr. chairman.

511
00:24:51,590 --> 00:24:54,024
What are we doing?

512
00:24:54,026 --> 00:24:55,626
We're stalling.

513
00:24:57,529 --> 00:24:58,863
Yes. Yes.

514
00:24:58,865 --> 00:25:02,266
My brother has many
admirable qualities.

515
00:25:02,268 --> 00:25:07,037
I-in some ways,
i can say I admire him.

516
00:25:07,039 --> 00:25:08,772
Too cold.

517
00:25:10,041 --> 00:25:12,977
I love my brother.

518
00:25:12,979 --> 00:25:16,580
But Ted kaczynski's brother
loved him, too.

519
00:25:16,582 --> 00:25:18,249
And he wanted to help.

520
00:25:18,251 --> 00:25:21,218
That's sanctimonious.

521
00:25:21,220 --> 00:25:23,687
I love my brother.

522
00:25:23,689 --> 00:25:27,791
He's a good person.
He has good in him.

523
00:25:27,793 --> 00:25:30,861
But the law is too important.

524
00:25:34,133 --> 00:25:35,833
Ah.

525
00:25:37,003 --> 00:25:38,869
Be right there, Howard!

526
00:25:44,977 --> 00:25:48,245
The law is too important.

527
00:25:48,247 --> 00:25:50,114
Hmm...

528
00:25:50,116 --> 00:25:53,317
Jimmy:<i> I sure shit wouldn't</i>
<i>be tellin' ya otherwise.</i>

529
00:25:53,319 --> 00:25:57,221
<i> But, yes...</i>
<i> It's the truth.</i>

530
00:25:58,323 --> 00:26:01,258
Chuck:<i> You'd go to such lengths</i>
<i> to humiliate me?</i>

531
00:26:01,260 --> 00:26:03,827
<i> I did it for Kim!</i>

532
00:26:03,829 --> 00:26:06,997
<i>She worked her butt off</i>
<i> to get mesa verde</i>

533
00:26:06,999 --> 00:26:11,201
<i>while you and Howard sat around</i>
<i>sipping scotch and chortling.</i>

534
00:26:11,203 --> 00:26:14,271
<i>Hamlin, Hamlin, mcgill --</i>
<i>more like scrooge and Marley!</i>

535
00:26:14,273 --> 00:26:18,676
<i>Kim deserves mesa verde --</i>
<i> not you, not hhm.</i>

536
00:26:18,678 --> 00:26:21,045
<i> She earned it,</i>
<i> and she needs it!</i>

537
00:26:21,047 --> 00:26:22,980
<i>I did it to help her,</i>

538
00:26:22,982 --> 00:26:26,584
<i>but i-i honestly didn't think</i>
<i>it would hurt you so bad.</i>

539
00:26:26,586 --> 00:26:29,153
<i>I thought you'd just say,</i>
<i>"oh, crap, I made a mistake,"</i>

540
00:26:29,155 --> 00:26:31,722
<i>and go on with your life,</i>
<i>like a normal person!</i>

541
00:26:31,724 --> 00:26:32,856
<i> But, oh, no!</i>

542
00:26:32,858 --> 00:26:34,959
<i> Wishful thinking!</i>

543
00:26:36,962 --> 00:26:39,830
<i> So, can I, uh,</i>
<i> tell Howard</i>

544
00:26:39,832 --> 00:26:42,800
<i> you're not quitting</i>
<i>or retiring or whatever?</i>

545
00:26:44,970 --> 00:26:48,272
<i>And can we take all this shit</i>
<i> down off the walls?</i>

546
00:26:50,342 --> 00:26:52,710
<i>I'm gonna go call Howard.</i>

547
00:26:52,712 --> 00:26:54,612
<i> Jimmy.</i>

548
00:26:54,614 --> 00:26:58,816
<i> You do realize</i>
<i>you just confessed to a felony?</i>

549
00:26:58,818 --> 00:27:00,951
<i> I guess.</i>

550
00:27:00,953 --> 00:27:02,786
<i> But you feel better,</i>
<i> right?</i>

551
00:27:04,089 --> 00:27:06,824
<i> Besides,</i>
<i>it's your word against mine.</i>

552
00:27:14,032 --> 00:27:16,233
Uh. Um.

553
00:27:18,003 --> 00:27:20,671
All right, uh,
Mr. alley, uh,

554
00:27:20,673 --> 00:27:22,840
we need to make accommodations
for your next witness.

555
00:27:22,842 --> 00:27:24,208
Is that correct?

556
00:27:24,210 --> 00:27:26,210
-Yes, Mr. chairman.
-All right.

557
00:27:26,212 --> 00:27:29,780
For those who don't know,
we need to prepare the room.

558
00:27:29,782 --> 00:27:32,850
Uh, the clerk is going to
collect your, uh, cellphones,

559
00:27:32,852 --> 00:27:35,285
watches, key fobs --
anything electrical.

560
00:27:35,287 --> 00:27:38,122
If you prefer not to,
please secure your items

561
00:27:38,124 --> 00:27:40,090
outside this room.
Thank you.

562
00:27:40,092 --> 00:27:42,026
Thank you
for understanding.

563
00:27:42,028 --> 00:27:43,227
Your phone, sir?

564
00:27:43,229 --> 00:27:45,062
I left it in the car.

565
00:28:34,079 --> 00:28:35,946
-Oh. Excuse me.
-Sorry.

566
00:28:35,948 --> 00:28:37,314
-That's yours.
-Thanks.

567
00:28:51,262 --> 00:28:53,964
Please raise
your right hand.

568
00:28:53,966 --> 00:28:56,433
Do you swear or affirm to tell
the truth, the whole truth,

569
00:28:56,435 --> 00:28:58,102
and nothing
but the truth?

570
00:28:58,104 --> 00:28:59,369
I do.

571
00:29:03,975 --> 00:29:05,776
Could you state
your name?

572
00:29:05,778 --> 00:29:07,377
Charles l. Mcgill.

573
00:29:07,379 --> 00:29:11,849
I'm a senior partner at the law
firm of Hamlin, Hamlin, mcgill.

574
00:29:11,851 --> 00:29:13,751
Can the court reporter
hear me?

575
00:29:13,753 --> 00:29:15,486
Yes, sir.
I can hear you fine.

576
00:29:15,488 --> 00:29:17,287
Mr. mcgill,
I'll try to be brief.

577
00:29:17,289 --> 00:29:19,289
We don't need to dwell
on the burglary

578
00:29:19,291 --> 00:29:21,091
or the assault
that you suffered.

579
00:29:21,093 --> 00:29:22,760
Thank you.
I appreciate that.

580
00:29:22,762 --> 00:29:25,195
Alley: What I would like
to hear about is this tape.

581
00:29:25,197 --> 00:29:26,997
What compelled you
to make it?

582
00:29:26,999 --> 00:29:29,800
I had a suspicion my brother
had tampered with documents

583
00:29:29,802 --> 00:29:31,201
in a case
i was working on.

584
00:29:31,203 --> 00:29:32,870
And why would he do that?

585
00:29:32,872 --> 00:29:35,038
Doesn't sound
particularly brotherly.

586
00:29:35,040 --> 00:29:37,841
I believe it was his hope
that the tainted documents

587
00:29:37,843 --> 00:29:39,943
would cause the client
to become disillusioned

588
00:29:39,945 --> 00:29:41,779
with my representation

589
00:29:41,781 --> 00:29:44,548
and return to their previous
attorney, Ms. wexler.

590
00:29:44,550 --> 00:29:47,985
Which, I should note,
is precisely what happened.

591
00:29:47,987 --> 00:29:49,520
Objection.

592
00:29:49,522 --> 00:29:52,422
I'm not saying Ms. wexler
knew what Jimmy was doing

593
00:29:52,424 --> 00:29:53,891
or had any involvement.

594
00:29:53,893 --> 00:29:55,993
I'm only stating
that it happened.

595
00:29:55,995 --> 00:29:57,227
Did you have any evidence

596
00:29:57,229 --> 00:29:59,263
to support your suspicions
about James?

597
00:29:59,265 --> 00:30:01,365
No.
My brother,

598
00:30:01,367 --> 00:30:04,268
whatever else can be said
of him, can be quite clever.

599
00:30:04,270 --> 00:30:06,370
Did an excellent job
of covering his tracks.

600
00:30:06,372 --> 00:30:08,138
Objection.

601
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:10,140
The witness has admitted there's
no corroborating evidence

602
00:30:10,142 --> 00:30:12,075
this supposed crime
even occurred.

603
00:30:12,077 --> 00:30:14,945
I'd like to hear
what he has to say.

604
00:30:14,947 --> 00:30:16,947
We're going to
continue.

605
00:30:16,949 --> 00:30:21,084
Uh, we'll extend you the same
latitude on cross, Ms. wexler.

606
00:30:21,086 --> 00:30:23,487
Go on, Mr. mcgill.

607
00:30:23,489 --> 00:30:25,055
Without
physical evidence,

608
00:30:25,057 --> 00:30:26,957
I felt that
a recorded confession --

609
00:30:26,959 --> 00:30:29,226
if I could get one --
was my best bet.

610
00:30:29,228 --> 00:30:31,995
On its own, I knew the tape
would be somewhat flimsy,

611
00:30:31,997 --> 00:30:33,230
but it was a start.

612
00:30:33,232 --> 00:30:36,466
A foundation
for a more ironclad case.

613
00:30:36,468 --> 00:30:38,535
I suppose that Jimmy
must have felt

614
00:30:38,537 --> 00:30:41,104
the tape was decisive evidence
on its own.

615
00:30:41,106 --> 00:30:43,106
Otherwise, he wouldn't have
broken in to destroy it.

616
00:30:43,108 --> 00:30:44,541
Objection.
More speculation.

617
00:30:44,543 --> 00:30:47,077
How can he know what was
going on in Jimmy's head?

618
00:30:47,079 --> 00:30:49,513
Sustained. We just need to hear
what happened, Mr. mcgill.

619
00:30:49,515 --> 00:30:52,182
Chuck:
I-i apologize.

620
00:30:52,184 --> 00:30:54,852
I recorded my brother
to build a case against him.

621
00:30:54,854 --> 00:30:56,453
Alley:
And at the time,

622
00:30:56,455 --> 00:30:58,522
would you say that you were
in possession of your faculties?

623
00:30:58,524 --> 00:31:00,123
All due respect, but --

624
00:31:00,125 --> 00:31:02,926
but you do sound somewhat
unhinged on the recording.

625
00:31:02,928 --> 00:31:04,161
Yes, I understand that.

626
00:31:04,163 --> 00:31:06,430
But what you heard
was theater.

627
00:31:06,432 --> 00:31:08,532
A performance,
play-acting.

628
00:31:08,534 --> 00:31:11,201
I exaggerated the symptoms
of my disease

629
00:31:11,203 --> 00:31:13,403
to extract the truth.

630
00:31:13,405 --> 00:31:15,873
Can we talk about your disease
for a moment?

631
00:31:15,875 --> 00:31:18,041
I'd like everybody here to be
on the same page about it.

632
00:31:18,043 --> 00:31:19,309
Of course.

633
00:31:19,311 --> 00:31:21,879
It is sometimes referred to
as ehs,

634
00:31:21,881 --> 00:31:24,147
electromagnetic
hypersensitivity.

635
00:31:24,149 --> 00:31:28,051
I describe it as an acute
allergy to electromagnetism.

636
00:31:28,053 --> 00:31:30,287
It's not a common condition,
is it?

637
00:31:30,289 --> 00:31:32,956
I know it sounds strange.
I do.

638
00:31:32,958 --> 00:31:36,126
But 30 years ago, no one had
heard of peanut allergies.

639
00:31:36,128 --> 00:31:38,028
But you admit
that no one --

640
00:31:38,030 --> 00:31:40,397
uh, no doctor --
has ever diagnosed you.

641
00:31:40,399 --> 00:31:44,301
Aids was not identified properly
until 1981.

642
00:31:44,303 --> 00:31:47,537
HIV wasn't known as the cause
until '83.

643
00:31:47,539 --> 00:31:51,041
These things take time
to unravel, even for doctors.

644
00:31:51,043 --> 00:31:52,509
Would you say
that your illness

645
00:31:52,511 --> 00:31:54,411
affects your ability
to think clearly?

646
00:31:54,413 --> 00:31:56,380
No.
It affects me physically.

647
00:31:56,382 --> 00:31:59,616
It causes me great pain.
However, I'm perfectly lucid.

648
00:31:59,618 --> 00:32:01,251
Thank you.

649
00:32:01,253 --> 00:32:04,655
Mr. mcgill, I have
only one more question for you.

650
00:32:06,157 --> 00:32:09,459
Do you hate
your brother?

651
00:32:09,461 --> 00:32:12,029
Absolutely not.

652
00:32:12,031 --> 00:32:14,398
I love my brother.

653
00:32:14,400 --> 00:32:18,235
There's nothing malicious
in Jimmy.

654
00:32:18,237 --> 00:32:20,704
He has a way of doing
the worst things

655
00:32:20,706 --> 00:32:23,340
for reasons
that sound almost noble.

656
00:32:24,609 --> 00:32:27,177
But what I know for sure
is that the law

657
00:32:27,179 --> 00:32:29,279
is too important
to be toyed with.

658
00:32:29,281 --> 00:32:32,015
It's mankind's greatest
achievement -- the rule of law,

659
00:32:32,017 --> 00:32:33,951
the idea that,
no matter who you are,

660
00:32:33,953 --> 00:32:36,153
your actions
have consequences.

661
00:32:37,556 --> 00:32:39,656
And the way my brother
treats the law --

662
00:32:39,658 --> 00:32:43,093
It breaks my heart.

663
00:32:43,095 --> 00:32:44,995
That's why I did what I did.

664
00:32:44,997 --> 00:32:48,465
Not to hurt him, but to protect
something that I hold sacred.

665
00:32:48,467 --> 00:32:50,467
Thank you, Mr. mcgill.

666
00:32:50,469 --> 00:32:52,469
The state bar rests.

667
00:32:55,740 --> 00:32:58,308
I think we need
to put on the brakes.

668
00:33:01,512 --> 00:33:04,581
I'm sorry. My co-counsel and i
need a moment to confer.

669
00:33:04,583 --> 00:33:07,718
Please be brief,
counselor.

670
00:33:07,720 --> 00:33:09,519
Yes, of course.

671
00:33:12,491 --> 00:33:14,658
She'll be here.

672
00:33:14,660 --> 00:33:16,626
Do you have anything
for cross?

673
00:33:16,628 --> 00:33:19,396
Uh, can I look
at your notes?

674
00:33:19,398 --> 00:33:20,397
Yeah, of course.

675
00:33:20,399 --> 00:33:21,765
Can we, um...

676
00:33:21,767 --> 00:33:23,633
Yeah.

677
00:33:34,045 --> 00:33:35,278
-Hey.
-Hey.

678
00:33:35,280 --> 00:33:36,713
So glad you made it.

679
00:33:39,785 --> 00:33:42,219
Mr. chairman, I'm sorry.

680
00:33:42,221 --> 00:33:46,056
Um, might I have a moment, uh,
to get a breath?

681
00:33:46,058 --> 00:33:48,125
Oh, of course,
Mr. mcgill.

682
00:33:48,127 --> 00:33:51,061
Uh, folks,
let's call this 15.

683
00:33:51,063 --> 00:33:55,198
Everybody, please be back
and ready to go on the hour.

684
00:34:02,607 --> 00:34:05,542
-Rebecca.
-Chuck.

685
00:34:05,544 --> 00:34:06,710
It's good to see you.

686
00:34:06,712 --> 00:34:09,713
I have to say,
I'm a bit surprised.

687
00:34:09,715 --> 00:34:11,548
Did Jimmy subpoena you?

688
00:34:11,550 --> 00:34:13,784
You're not on the witness list.
You don't have to testify.

689
00:34:13,786 --> 00:34:16,386
No, no, no, no.
I'm not here for that.

690
00:34:16,388 --> 00:34:18,655
Well, what, then?

691
00:34:18,657 --> 00:34:21,425
Chuck,
i wish you'd told me.

692
00:34:21,427 --> 00:34:25,128
I-i can't believe what
you've been going through.

693
00:34:25,130 --> 00:34:26,663
How long has it been?

694
00:34:26,665 --> 00:34:28,098
Ah.

695
00:34:28,100 --> 00:34:29,766
You're here to help.

696
00:34:29,768 --> 00:34:32,235
Because all this
is so stressful for me.

697
00:34:33,305 --> 00:34:34,538
Is that
what Jimmy told you?

698
00:34:34,540 --> 00:34:36,306
He's worried about you, Chuck.

699
00:34:36,308 --> 00:34:38,542
In spite of everything that's
happened between the two of you,

700
00:34:38,544 --> 00:34:39,609
he -- he cares.

701
00:34:39,611 --> 00:34:40,777
What exactly
did he say?

702
00:34:40,779 --> 00:34:43,280
Um, well,
that you had been sick.

703
00:34:43,282 --> 00:34:44,714
Allergic to electricity?

704
00:34:44,716 --> 00:34:47,117
He sent me pictures
of the house.

705
00:34:47,119 --> 00:34:49,820
Chuck, my god.

706
00:34:49,822 --> 00:34:51,822
Why didn't you tell me?

707
00:34:51,824 --> 00:34:54,091
I didn't want
to upset you.

708
00:34:54,093 --> 00:34:56,126
Worry you
unnecessarily.

709
00:34:57,696 --> 00:34:59,663
But now you're here.

710
00:34:59,665 --> 00:35:01,531
And now you know.

711
00:35:03,835 --> 00:35:06,470
I came because I thought
it was the right thing.

712
00:35:06,472 --> 00:35:09,239
I thought -- I don't know --
that you'd want me to.

713
00:35:09,241 --> 00:35:12,843
But I guess that I'm more
of a distraction.

714
00:35:12,845 --> 00:35:14,244
So, uh...

715
00:35:14,246 --> 00:35:16,279
I'm gonna be in town
for a few days,

716
00:35:16,281 --> 00:35:19,516
and I would love
to spend some time with you.

717
00:35:19,518 --> 00:35:21,585
But right now,
i-i think I should go.

718
00:35:21,587 --> 00:35:23,520
No. No, no, please.
I want you to stay.

719
00:35:23,522 --> 00:35:25,455
Really?
You don't seem happy to see me.

720
00:35:25,457 --> 00:35:27,124
I am.

721
00:35:27,126 --> 00:35:29,759
Just surprised,
that's all.

722
00:35:29,761 --> 00:35:32,429
Please, stay.

723
00:35:32,431 --> 00:35:33,763
Are you sure?

724
00:35:33,765 --> 00:35:35,365
Yes, I'm sure.

725
00:35:35,367 --> 00:35:38,201
You've been sold
a bill of goods, Rebecca.

726
00:35:38,203 --> 00:35:41,271
I want you
to see what's what.

727
00:35:49,714 --> 00:35:53,416
She's not
what I expected.

728
00:35:53,418 --> 00:35:55,719
Oh, yeah?
What'd you expect?

729
00:35:55,721 --> 00:35:58,355
I don't know.
Just...

730
00:35:58,357 --> 00:35:59,656
Not her.

731
00:36:03,629 --> 00:36:06,563
You know, she's gonna hate you
when this is over.

732
00:36:07,665 --> 00:36:09,566
Yep.

733
00:36:21,279 --> 00:36:23,446
All right,
uh, Mr. mcgill,

734
00:36:23,448 --> 00:36:24,581
I'll remind you
you're still under oath.

735
00:36:24,583 --> 00:36:26,316
I understand.

736
00:36:26,318 --> 00:36:28,585
At this time, I'd like
to turn cross-examination over

737
00:36:28,587 --> 00:36:30,453
to my co-counsel,
James mcgill.

738
00:36:36,728 --> 00:36:39,462
Uh, well, there's been a lot
of fuss about it,

739
00:36:39,464 --> 00:36:42,566
but you and I have never really
talked about this tape you made.

740
00:36:42,568 --> 00:36:43,967
We lost the opportunity

741
00:36:43,969 --> 00:36:46,836
when you burglarized my house
to destroy it.

742
00:36:46,838 --> 00:36:48,205
Fair enough.

743
00:36:48,207 --> 00:36:49,806
Um, and I was
in the wrong there.

744
00:36:49,808 --> 00:36:53,276
But, still, I'd like
to try and follow your story

745
00:36:53,278 --> 00:36:55,512
of why and how
you recorded it.

746
00:36:55,514 --> 00:36:57,948
Oh, is this where you claim
the tape is spurious?

747
00:36:57,950 --> 00:36:59,783
That it's not really
your voice?

748
00:36:59,785 --> 00:37:02,652
No.
That's me on the tape.

749
00:37:02,654 --> 00:37:04,688
But, still,
i have some questions.

750
00:37:04,690 --> 00:37:06,223
Like, the recorder,

751
00:37:06,225 --> 00:37:08,558
it must've hurt like hell
for you to touch that.

752
00:37:08,560 --> 00:37:11,428
There was a degree
of discomfort, that's true.

753
00:37:11,430 --> 00:37:12,729
And where
did you hide it?

754
00:37:12,731 --> 00:37:14,431
I mean,
the sound's pretty clear,

755
00:37:14,433 --> 00:37:16,466
so it wasn't in
the couch cushions, was it?

756
00:37:16,468 --> 00:37:19,002
Tucked under a space blanket.
Out of sight.

757
00:37:19,004 --> 00:37:20,470
Wow.

758
00:37:20,472 --> 00:37:22,272
So there's no chance
i would see it.

759
00:37:22,274 --> 00:37:23,506
Not with the state
your place was in.

760
00:37:23,508 --> 00:37:25,442
Isn't that right?
I suppose.

761
00:37:25,444 --> 00:37:28,411
Would you like to set the scene
for the disciplinary committee?

762
00:37:28,413 --> 00:37:30,380
Tell them, you know,
what your house looked like

763
00:37:30,382 --> 00:37:31,615
at the time
of the recording.

764
00:37:31,617 --> 00:37:33,984
Objection.
Relevance?

765
00:37:33,986 --> 00:37:36,319
Well, the circumstances
of the recording

766
00:37:36,321 --> 00:37:37,621
are materially relevant.

767
00:37:37,623 --> 00:37:39,422
How can you know
what the tape really means

768
00:37:39,424 --> 00:37:41,758
unless you know what was
going on when it was recorded?

769
00:37:41,760 --> 00:37:44,294
Overruled. The witness
can answer the question.

770
00:37:44,296 --> 00:37:48,598
I covered most of the walls with
foil-scrim-kraft insulation.

771
00:37:48,600 --> 00:37:52,469
I also hung a number
of space blankets.

772
00:37:52,471 --> 00:37:53,837
Compact mylar sheets.

773
00:37:53,839 --> 00:37:55,572
They insulate and protect

774
00:37:55,574 --> 00:37:58,408
against mild
electromagnetic radiation.

775
00:37:58,876 --> 00:38:02,445
All right, so, shiny
insulation and space blankets

776
00:38:02,447 --> 00:38:04,681
all over the walls
and the ceiling.

777
00:38:04,683 --> 00:38:07,317
It was like being
inside of a disco ball.

778
00:38:07,319 --> 00:38:09,653
Do you have a point?

779
00:38:09,655 --> 00:38:12,555
Well, um, I'm impressed

780
00:38:12,557 --> 00:38:14,958
by how much work
went into entrapping me.

781
00:38:14,960 --> 00:38:16,026
You went all out.

782
00:38:16,028 --> 00:38:17,894
I didn't entrap you.

783
00:38:17,896 --> 00:38:20,630
I provoked an admission
in adverse interest.

784
00:38:20,632 --> 00:38:22,499
That's not
the same thing.

785
00:38:23,834 --> 00:38:26,836
How did you know
it would work?

786
00:38:26,838 --> 00:38:28,371
What do you mean?

787
00:38:28,373 --> 00:38:31,374
How did you know your
"provocation" would work?

788
00:38:31,376 --> 00:38:33,877
Why'd you think a bunch
of shiny plastic

789
00:38:33,879 --> 00:38:35,812
would make me
say anything?

790
00:38:35,814 --> 00:38:39,549
Isn't it because you knew
that it was precisely the thing

791
00:38:39,551 --> 00:38:41,551
that would worry me
so much

792
00:38:41,553 --> 00:38:43,720
that I'd say anything
to talk you down?

793
00:38:43,722 --> 00:38:44,721
Objection.

794
00:38:44,723 --> 00:38:46,523
Okay. Withdrawn.

795
00:38:46,525 --> 00:38:49,592
Let's -- let's get back
to your house,

796
00:38:49,594 --> 00:38:52,095
every surface
covered in tinfoil.

797
00:38:52,097 --> 00:38:54,664
Nothing crazy
about that, huh?

798
00:38:54,666 --> 00:38:59,636
As I've said,
i was playing up my condition.

799
00:38:59,638 --> 00:39:01,504
Usually, it's
a perfectly normal house.

800
00:39:01,506 --> 00:39:02,939
You think your house
is normal?

801
00:39:02,941 --> 00:39:05,709
Can I call your attention
to exhibit nine?

802
00:39:10,514 --> 00:39:12,382
This is your house,
right?

803
00:39:12,384 --> 00:39:13,650
Yes.

804
00:39:13,652 --> 00:39:16,453
So, exposed wires.

805
00:39:17,723 --> 00:39:20,623
There's a camp stove.

806
00:39:20,625 --> 00:39:23,827
There's a lantern
on top of newspapers.

807
00:39:23,829 --> 00:39:25,061
You call this normal?

808
00:39:25,063 --> 00:39:27,564
I call them adaptations.

809
00:39:27,566 --> 00:39:30,934
A prophylactic measure for
a physical, medical condition.

810
00:39:30,936 --> 00:39:33,503
Did the doctor who granted me
guardianship for you

811
00:39:33,505 --> 00:39:34,938
think this was
a physical condition?

812
00:39:34,940 --> 00:39:36,373
Objection.

813
00:39:36,375 --> 00:39:37,841
You can't introduce a teg
as evidence.

814
00:39:37,843 --> 00:39:40,143
Besides which,
the panel has already ruled

815
00:39:40,145 --> 00:39:42,879
that Mr. mcgill's mental health
is not at issue.

816
00:39:42,881 --> 00:39:45,382
No, the state bar opened
the door to this on direct

817
00:39:45,384 --> 00:39:48,485
when the witness talked about
his supposed "play-acting."

818
00:39:48,487 --> 00:39:51,554
Allowing me to follow up
on cross is only reasonable.

819
00:39:51,556 --> 00:39:53,056
We discussed
the physical allergy,

820
00:39:53,058 --> 00:39:54,124
not a mental disability.

821
00:39:54,126 --> 00:39:55,492
Potato, po-tah-to.

822
00:39:55,494 --> 00:39:56,926
It comes down to this --

823
00:39:56,928 --> 00:39:59,763
in order to understand
what I was thinking,

824
00:39:59,765 --> 00:40:02,532
you need to see Chuck
through my eyes.

825
00:40:02,534 --> 00:40:06,002
You need to know if I believed
that tape was evidence.

826
00:40:06,004 --> 00:40:08,605
And I say it was evidence
of only one thing --

827
00:40:08,607 --> 00:40:11,007
my brother hates me.

828
00:40:11,009 --> 00:40:15,078
Now, he claims that he lied to
me to get me to tell the truth.

829
00:40:15,080 --> 00:40:16,613
And I'm telling you

830
00:40:16,615 --> 00:40:19,449
I lied to my brother
to make him feel better.

831
00:40:19,451 --> 00:40:21,050
Which of us you believe

832
00:40:21,052 --> 00:40:25,088
depends on how we all understand
the mind of Charles mcgill.

833
00:40:26,724 --> 00:40:30,760
Well, we did promise the defense
some leeway.

834
00:40:30,762 --> 00:40:32,162
You may proceed.

835
00:40:32,164 --> 00:40:35,064
-Thank you, Mr. chairman.
-But watch yourself.

836
00:40:42,139 --> 00:40:44,607
Chuck, I'd like to go back
a little further,

837
00:40:44,609 --> 00:40:46,943
talk about when these symptoms
first started.

838
00:40:46,945 --> 00:40:50,814
It was shortly after you were
divorced, is that right?

839
00:40:52,450 --> 00:40:54,050
Yes.

840
00:40:54,052 --> 00:40:56,753
You think the stress of the
divorce brought on the illness?

841
00:40:56,755 --> 00:40:58,988
I doubt it.
It was an amicable split.

842
00:40:58,990 --> 00:41:01,558
My ex-wife and i
are still on good terms.

843
00:41:01,560 --> 00:41:04,961
In fact, your ex-wife is present
with us today, is she not?

844
00:41:04,963 --> 00:41:06,763
When was the last time
you two saw each other?

845
00:41:06,765 --> 00:41:08,698
Objection.
This is not family court.

846
00:41:08,700 --> 00:41:11,134
We're not here to re-litigate
the witness' divorce.

847
00:41:11,136 --> 00:41:13,136
I can't see what purpose
this serves.

848
00:41:13,138 --> 00:41:14,904
I can.

849
00:41:14,906 --> 00:41:16,539
I'll tell you
why my brother

850
00:41:16,541 --> 00:41:18,208
brought my ex-wife
to this hearing.

851
00:41:18,210 --> 00:41:24,047
4,000 miles she came,
lured by concern for me.

852
00:41:24,049 --> 00:41:27,016
What Jimmy's driving at
is the last time I saw her,

853
00:41:27,018 --> 00:41:28,585
I covered up my illness.

854
00:41:28,587 --> 00:41:30,987
I'd been suffering from it
for some time,

855
00:41:30,989 --> 00:41:34,524
but I went to great lengths
to conceal that fact from her.

856
00:41:36,060 --> 00:41:39,729
I'm sorry I deceived you,
Rebecca.

857
00:41:40,966 --> 00:41:43,766
I didn't want you
to think less of me.

858
00:41:45,870 --> 00:41:48,104
Now Jimmy has outed me
in front of you.

859
00:41:48,106 --> 00:41:50,540
You know why?

860
00:41:50,542 --> 00:41:51,841
To rattle me.

861
00:41:51,843 --> 00:41:53,943
He knows I still have a...

862
00:41:53,945 --> 00:41:58,147
Lot of,
feeling for my ex-wife.

863
00:41:58,149 --> 00:42:01,050
He's hoping
this will break me down.

864
00:42:01,052 --> 00:42:03,186
Split me apart
at the seams,

865
00:42:03,188 --> 00:42:07,090
like a murderer confessing
on an episode of "Perry Mason."

866
00:42:07,092 --> 00:42:10,693
Well, I'm sorry
to disappoint you, Jimmy.

867
00:42:12,296 --> 00:42:16,633
Have I answered your questions
to your satisfaction?

868
00:42:16,635 --> 00:42:19,035
Do you have
anything else?

869
00:42:20,738 --> 00:42:22,739
Yeah, I do.

870
00:42:22,741 --> 00:42:25,308
Earlier, you talked about
other diseases.

871
00:42:25,310 --> 00:42:27,544
Physical conditions,
you said.

872
00:42:27,546 --> 00:42:30,547
Uh, so, okay, if you'd had,
um -- I don't know --

873
00:42:30,549 --> 00:42:34,784
lung cancer, would you
have told Rebecca then?

874
00:42:35,987 --> 00:42:38,087
If that had been the case,
maybe.

875
00:42:38,089 --> 00:42:39,188
I might have.

876
00:42:39,190 --> 00:42:40,690
So how is this different?

877
00:42:40,692 --> 00:42:42,792
Mr. mcgill.
Move it along.

878
00:42:42,794 --> 00:42:44,227
You don't
have to answer that.

879
00:42:44,229 --> 00:42:45,995
I want to get down
to brass tacks.

880
00:42:45,997 --> 00:42:47,897
I want to be very,
very specific here.

881
00:42:47,899 --> 00:42:50,233
This illness,
what does it feel like?

882
00:42:50,235 --> 00:42:52,168
You mentioned
it's painful.

883
00:42:52,170 --> 00:42:54,003
It is.

884
00:42:54,005 --> 00:42:57,273
There's a tightness in my chest,
difficulty breathing,

885
00:42:57,275 --> 00:43:00,176
and pain, burning pain.

886
00:43:00,178 --> 00:43:02,312
The pain
spreads everywhere.

887
00:43:02,314 --> 00:43:04,914
Sounds horrible.
Does it hurt right now?

888
00:43:04,916 --> 00:43:07,250
There's always
some discomfort, yes.

889
00:43:07,252 --> 00:43:10,019
Electricity is everywhere
in the modern world.

890
00:43:11,656 --> 00:43:14,891
But I very much appreciate
the indulgence of the panel

891
00:43:14,893 --> 00:43:16,859
for their accommodation
here today.

892
00:43:16,861 --> 00:43:18,995
I can handle this fine.

893
00:43:22,634 --> 00:43:25,134
Right, so, with the lights out,
you don't feel them?

894
00:43:25,136 --> 00:43:26,903
Chuck: If the current's
not flowing, no.

895
00:43:26,905 --> 00:43:29,072
Oh. Sorry about
the exit signs.

896
00:43:29,074 --> 00:43:30,974
I guess they couldn't
kill those for you.

897
00:43:30,976 --> 00:43:33,276
Well, they're not drawing much
current, and they're far away.

898
00:43:34,713 --> 00:43:36,846
Intensity drops off
with distance,

899
00:43:36,848 --> 00:43:38,314
per the inverse-square law.

900
00:43:38,316 --> 00:43:39,749
Okay, whoa!

901
00:43:39,751 --> 00:43:41,684
Inverse-square --
I'm not a physicist.

902
00:43:41,686 --> 00:43:43,653
Could you dumb that down a shade
for me?

903
00:43:43,655 --> 00:43:45,221
The farther away it is,

904
00:43:45,223 --> 00:43:47,824
the stronger the source
needs to be to have an effect.

905
00:43:47,826 --> 00:43:49,392
Got it.
Got it.

906
00:43:49,394 --> 00:43:52,061
So, if I had a small battery,
say, from a watch or something,

907
00:43:52,063 --> 00:43:55,098
and I got it close to you,
close to your skin, you'd know?

908
00:43:55,100 --> 00:43:56,366
I would feel it, yes.

909
00:43:56,368 --> 00:43:57,867
Can you feel more current

910
00:43:57,869 --> 00:43:59,168
coming from any particular
direction right now?

911
00:43:59,170 --> 00:44:01,771
Uh, from that back wall

912
00:44:01,773 --> 00:44:04,207
or, uh, from over there

913
00:44:04,209 --> 00:44:05,908
or up through the floor?

914
00:44:05,910 --> 00:44:08,277
Can you tell us where
the nearest source is

915
00:44:08,279 --> 00:44:09,946
right now?

916
00:44:13,717 --> 00:44:16,386
Jimmy, do you have something
in your pocket?

917
00:44:18,355 --> 00:44:21,357
Yes, I do,
as a matter of fact.

918
00:44:24,161 --> 00:44:25,928
My cellphone.

919
00:44:25,930 --> 00:44:29,999
From this distance, you should
feel it, and you don't, do you?

920
00:44:30,001 --> 00:44:33,202
Mr. mcgill, you were warned to
leave your electronics outside.

921
00:44:34,004 --> 00:44:35,805
It's all right.

922
00:44:35,807 --> 00:44:38,207
It's all right.

923
00:44:38,209 --> 00:44:39,375
May I?

924
00:44:40,944 --> 00:44:43,179
Ah.

925
00:44:45,149 --> 00:44:48,751
Just as I thought.
There's no battery in here.

926
00:44:48,753 --> 00:44:50,420
You removed the battery.

927
00:44:52,123 --> 00:44:55,258
That's a sorry
little trick, isn't it?

928
00:44:55,260 --> 00:44:58,127
Yeah, you got me, Chuck.
Dead to rights.

929
00:44:58,129 --> 00:45:00,763
I removed the battery.

930
00:45:00,765 --> 00:45:02,899
-Objection.
-Sustained.

931
00:45:02,901 --> 00:45:04,967
Y-you've taken all the leeway
you're getting, Mr. mcgill.

932
00:45:04,969 --> 00:45:06,102
Wrap it up fast.

933
00:45:06,104 --> 00:45:09,405
God, Jimmy.

934
00:45:09,407 --> 00:45:11,741
Don't you know by now
this is real?

935
00:45:11,743 --> 00:45:12,942
I feel this.

936
00:45:12,944 --> 00:45:15,178
It's a physical response
to stimuli.

937
00:45:15,180 --> 00:45:17,847
It's not a quirk.

938
00:45:19,284 --> 00:45:21,751
What do I have to do
to prove it to you?

939
00:45:21,753 --> 00:45:23,186
I don't know, Chuck.

940
00:45:23,188 --> 00:45:26,189
Could you reach into
your breast pocket

941
00:45:26,191 --> 00:45:28,157
and tell me what's there?

942
00:45:29,427 --> 00:45:31,160
What now?

943
00:45:37,101 --> 00:45:39,969
Can you tell the court
what that was?

944
00:45:42,106 --> 00:45:44,140
-A battery.
-Mr. chairman, please.

945
00:45:44,142 --> 00:45:45,842
Do you recognize
that man in back?

946
00:45:45,844 --> 00:45:48,411
His name is huell babineaux.
He's on our witness list.

947
00:45:48,413 --> 00:45:50,379
You bumped into him
in the stairway.

948
00:45:50,381 --> 00:45:53,382
He'll testify he planted this
fully charged battery on you

949
00:45:53,384 --> 00:45:55,084
over
an hour and a half ago.

950
00:45:55,086 --> 00:45:56,452
Hour and 43 minutes ago.

951
00:45:56,454 --> 00:45:59,756
An hour and 43 minutes.
Thank you, Mr. babineaux.

952
00:45:59,758 --> 00:46:01,257
And you felt nothing.

953
00:46:01,259 --> 00:46:02,425
No, no, no.

954
00:46:02,427 --> 00:46:03,826
No, no. It's a trick.
It has to --

955
00:46:03,828 --> 00:46:05,428
enough is enough.

956
00:46:05,430 --> 00:46:08,030
I submit that Mr. mcgill's
mental illness is a non-issue.

957
00:46:08,032 --> 00:46:10,299
-If he were schizophrenic...
-Schizo--

958
00:46:10,301 --> 00:46:12,268
...it wouldn't take away from
the fact that the defendant --
i am not crazy!

959
00:46:16,140 --> 00:46:18,107
I am not crazy.

960
00:46:18,109 --> 00:46:20,877
I know he swapped
those numbers.

961
00:46:20,879 --> 00:46:23,112
I knew it was 1216.

962
00:46:23,114 --> 00:46:24,447
One after magna carta.

963
00:46:24,449 --> 00:46:26,849
As if I could ever
make such a mistake.

964
00:46:26,851 --> 00:46:27,984
Never. Never!

965
00:46:27,986 --> 00:46:30,553
I just --
i just couldn't prove it.

966
00:46:30,555 --> 00:46:32,255
H-h-he covered his tracks.

967
00:46:32,257 --> 00:46:34,824
He got that idiot at
the copy shop to lie for him.

968
00:46:34,826 --> 00:46:37,160
Alley: Mr. mcgill, please.
You don't have to go in--

969
00:46:37,162 --> 00:46:38,795
you think
this is something?

970
00:46:38,797 --> 00:46:40,863
You think this is bad,
this -- this chicanery?

971
00:46:40,865 --> 00:46:43,466
He's done worse.
That billboard!

972
00:46:43,468 --> 00:46:46,502
Are you telling me that a man
just happens to fall like that?

973
00:46:46,504 --> 00:46:48,838
No.
He orchestrated it!

974
00:46:48,840 --> 00:46:50,406
Jimmy!

975
00:46:50,408 --> 00:46:53,976
He defecated
through a sunroof!

976
00:46:53,978 --> 00:46:57,313
And I saved him,
and I shouldn't have.

977
00:46:57,315 --> 00:46:59,248
I took him into my own firm.

978
00:46:59,250 --> 00:47:01,584
What was I thinking?!

979
00:47:01,586 --> 00:47:03,519
He'll never change.

980
00:47:03,521 --> 00:47:05,021
He'll<i> never</i> change.

981
00:47:05,023 --> 00:47:07,490
Ever since he was 9,
always the same.

982
00:47:07,492 --> 00:47:10,326
Couldn't keep his hands
out of the cash drawer.

983
00:47:10,328 --> 00:47:12,094
But not our Jimmy.

984
00:47:12,096 --> 00:47:14,430
Couldn't be precious Jimmy!

985
00:47:14,432 --> 00:47:16,999
Stealing them blind.

986
00:47:17,001 --> 00:47:18,968
And he gets to be a lawyer?!

987
00:47:18,970 --> 00:47:21,103
What a sick joke!

988
00:47:21,105 --> 00:47:23,973
I should have stopped him
when I had the chance!

989
00:47:23,975 --> 00:47:25,608
And you --
you have to stop him!

990
00:47:25,610 --> 00:47:27,276
You --

991
00:47:49,367 --> 00:47:51,234
I apologize.

992
00:47:53,103 --> 00:47:55,538
I lost my train of thought.

993
00:47:58,976 --> 00:48:01,244
I got carried away.

994
00:48:06,516 --> 00:48:08,384
Do you have
anything else?

995
00:48:10,520 --> 00:48:14,023
No. Nothing further.

